    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical Note</head>
      <p>Seamus Deane (1940-), Irish poet and educator, was born in <geogname source="geonames"
          authfilenumber="2643736">Derry, Northern Ireland</geogname>. He attended <corpname
          source="dbpedia" authfilenumber="Queen's_University_Belfast">Queen's
        University</corpname>, Belfast and <corpname source="dbpedia"
          authfilenumber="Cambridge_University">Cambridge University</corpname>. He was a professor
        of English and
        <?oxy_comment_start author="saritaalami" timestamp="20130623T225357-0400" comment="I didn&apos;t tag the United States here because I don&apos;t think the subject American Literature merits it."?>American
        Literature<?oxy_comment_end?> at University College, Dublin and a professor of
        <?oxy_comment_start author="saritaalami" timestamp="20130623T225613-0400" comment="I didn&apos;t tag Ireland here for the same reason."?>Irish
        Studies<?oxy_comment_end?> at the <corpname
          source="dbpedia" authfilenumber="University_of_Notre_Dame">University of Notre Dame</corpname>. He was also a founding director
        of the Field Day Theatre Company, along with <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="38545317">David Hammond</persname>, <persname source="viaf"
          authfilenumber="109557338">Seamus Heaney</persname>, and <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="108291535">Tom Paulin</persname>. Deane has published
        several works of poetry and non-fiction, as well as one novel. His collections of poetry
        include Gradual Wars, Rumors and History Lessons; his non-fiction includes Heroic Styles:
        The Tradition of an Idea, Celtic Revivals: Essays in Modern Irish Literature, A Short
        History of <geogname source="geonames" authfilenumber="2963597">Irish</geogname> Literature, Strange Country, and <geogname source="geonames" authfilenumber="3017382">French</geogname> Revolution and Enlightenment in
          <?oxy_delete author="namedropper" timestamp="20130614T123418-0400" content="England"?><?oxy_insert_start author="namedropper" timestamp="20130614T123418-0400" comment="England Listen/ˈɪŋɡlənd/ is a country that is part of the United Kingdom. It shares land borders with Scotland to the north and Wales to the west; the Irish Sea is to the north west, the Celtic Sea to the south west, while the North Sea to the east and the English Channel to the south separate it from continental Europe. Most of England comprises the central and southern part of the island of Great Britain in the North Atlantic."?><geogname
          source="geonames" authfilenumber="3333218"
        >England</geogname><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_comment_start author="saritaalami" timestamp="20130621T013954-0400" comment="I&apos;m tagging geographic names even when they appear as part of book/publication titles."?>,<?oxy_comment_end?>
        1789-1832. His novel, Reading in the Dark, was nominated for a Booker Prize in 1996.</p>
      
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
      <p>The collection consists of the papers of Irish poet and educator Seamus Deane.  It contains writings by Deane and others, correspondence, journals and business records.  Writings by others include works by <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="76315726">Brian Friel</persname> and <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="91961511">Thomas Kilroy</persname>.  The collection also contains materials relating to Seamus Heaney's work, particularly a draft of his 1975 poetry collection North.  Significant correspondents include <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="109176234">Denis Donoghue</persname>, Seamus Heaney (restricted), <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="34500781">Thomas Kinsella</persname>, <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="39398205">Michael</persname> and Evelyn Longley, <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="120096893">Medbh McGuckian</persname>, <persname source="viaf" authfilenumber="110228045">Derek Mahon</persname>, and Tom Paulin.</p>
    </scopecontent>
